Problem.Description:
Have you used Git? It is a distributed revision control system with an emphasis on speed, data integrity, and support for distributed, non-linear workflows. Git was initially designed and developed by Linus Torvalds for Linux kernel development in 2005, and has since become the most widely adopted version control system for software development.

There is a command “diff” in Git. It will give you the result like this:


The utility will process your file, and find the difference between its current version and previous version to record the changes you made. So you can collaborate with other team members, manage branchs, and rollback changes.

As you see, the diff utility compare the file line by line. It colors the lines in previous but not in current version (deletions) red, the lines not in previous but in current version (additions) green, and the lines same in both versions white. It always try its best to find the most sequence of lines same in common, and output human readable report to tell user the changes of the file.

To simplify the problem, you should write a program to read the previous and current version of some files. For each file, output the diff report like above. The common lines should be as more as possible and output deletions in front of additions. Add a space (' ') in front of every common lines, a plus sign ('+') in front of every addition lines, a minus sign ('-') in front of every deletion lines.
Problem.InputSpec: There are multiple test cases. They are separated by a line “=====” (a line with 5 equal signs). In each case, describing a file, the previous and current content of the file are separated by a line “-----” (a line with 5 minus signs). The lines of file content will not be more than 5000.
Problem.OutputSpec: For each case, output the diff report as described above. If there are multiple solutions, any one will be accepted. There should be a line “=====” (a line with 5 equal signs) between each case.
